<header>
    <h1>THE UNDERGROUND EXCHANGE</h1>
    <p class="small-note">Occupied Territory — 1943 • Access Level: Restricted</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

    <div class="warning-box">
        <strong>NOTICE:</strong>  
        This is a <strong>fictional, historical-themed black market</strong> representing the kind of 
        underground trade that occurred during WWII. Everything here is fabricated for 
        <strong>storytelling, world-building, and educational use only.</strong>
    </div>

    <p>
        Beneath the cracked stone of the old metro tunnels, past the rusted gate and the dim lanterns,
        traders whisper and barter what the war has taken from everyday life.  
        Smoky air hangs heavy, boots scrape on the damp floor, and everyone keeps one eye on the tunnel entrance.
    </p>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <!-- ITEMS START -->

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Ration Coupon Books (Forged & Stolen)</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Poorly printed, ink-smudged ration books circulating among civilians and resistance members.</p>
        <p><strong>Details:</strong> Sugar, wheat, fuel, and fabric coupons in inconsistent quantities.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 4–7 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Contraband Coffee & Tea</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Smuggled beans from neutral territories. Usually stale, sometimes moldy.</p>
        <p><strong>Details:</strong> Wrapped in oil-stained cloth with foreign merchant stamps scraped off.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 10–18 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Dented Canned Goods</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Illicit tins of meat, condensed milk, or fish salvaged from bombed depots.</p>
        <p><strong>Notes:</strong> Labels often partially burned; contents not guaranteed safe.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 6–12 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Bootleg Soap & Candles</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Weak soap bars and low-grade candles made from questionable animal fat.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 3 Reichsmarks per bundle (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Smuggled Radio Parts</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Loose vacuum tubes, wires, dials, and cracked tuning knobs.</p>
        <p><strong>Context:</strong> Often used by resistance groups to rebuild confiscated transmitters.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 30–55 Reichsmarks per set (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Forged Identification Papers</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Counterfeit worker permits and travel passes.</p>
        <p><strong>Quality:</strong> Ranges from “passable in poor light” to “likely to get you arrested.”</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 40–100 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Underground Press Leaflets</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Secret anti-occupation newsletters printed with stolen ink.</p>
        <p><strong>Condition:</strong> Smudged, rushed, often water-damaged.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 1 Reichsmark (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Medical Supplies (Surplus)</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Bandages, morphine vials, ointments, and cracked medical tins.</p>
        <p><strong>Notes:</strong> Most items outdated or scavenged from destroyed field stations.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 15–60 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Illicit Clothing & Textiles</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Patchwork garments, mismatched buttons, thin winter coats.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 8–25 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Scrap Metal & Tools</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Bent nails, rusted pliers, broken screwdrivers, metal offcuts.</p>
        <p><strong>Used by:</strong> Civilians, repairmen, saboteurs.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 2–15 Reichsmarks depending on condition (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Bootleg Alcohol</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Harsh homemade spirits stored in reused medicine bottles.</p>
        <p><strong>Notes:</strong> Potency unpredictable; usually terrible.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 6–14 Reichsmarks (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="item">
        <h2>Secret Messages (Courier Services)</h2>
        <p><strong>Description:</strong> Folded notes hidden inside bread loaves, coat linings, or shoe soles.</p>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> 12 Reichsmarks per delivery (fictional)</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ITEMS END -->

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <p>
        In the shadows, traders move quickly—no one lingers.  
        Footsteps echo down the tunnel, and lanterns sway as someone whispers the coded phrase:  
        <em>“The nightingale sings after midnight.”</em>
    </p>

